                            <comment id="18531" author="springboy" created="Tue, 11 Jul 2006 21:45:04 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Fixed. Thanks for spotting this. I couldn&apos;t see the wood for the trees there as I was writing the documentatio in DocBook. Thanks.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cheers&lt;br/&gt;
Rick&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="18739" author="dohunt" created="Mon, 24 Jul 2006 06:17:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I looked at the new doc and it does address the @Transactional piece.  However it doesn&apos;t state how you could force the transaction to execute first as in the other example (where is the order attribute of the transaction), nor does it show an example of using @Transactional with @Aspect version of this example.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thanks!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="18747" author="springboy" created="Mon, 24 Jul 2006 19:43:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Don&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Indeed, it doesn&apos;t tell you how to order the transactional advice, because there is (as yet) no way to do that &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/images/icons/emoticons/sad.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt; I have raised this issue before with other of the Spring dev team, but no-one has as yet come up with a firm answer. One answer would be to expose an order attribute on the &amp;lt;tx:annotation-driven/&amp;gt; tag.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ll add an example that shows the @Aspect-style too.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ll address these shortcomings in time for 2.0 final. Thanks for being so thorough.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cheers&lt;br/&gt;
Rick&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
